Germany, Year Zero
May 8 always reminds me of the year 1945, for the end of the war in Europe was truly a pivotal moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our small street, in the outskirts of western Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide as I did after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the start of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
The Nazis having left, the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We looted the shops in the neighborhood. I still have some volumes of romantic poetry that I recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying armies were committing all excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was taken directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and charged with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply office.
For a certain time, there was neither electricity nor transportation, nor any organized life.
Victory or liberation?
For the Germans, it was a delicate question, even if for our family it was clearly a liberation in every sense of the word.
For what purpose?
For what future?
"You must help," my mother said.
I proposed my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in delivering basic food supplies to a few distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card as a "victim of fascism," while others wore an Iron Cross earned late for their service to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombing raids, almost everyone was mourning the loss of loved ones.
Yet, this phase didn't last.
It's almost unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle".
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and especially accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
In contrast, after a brief period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
A year after the end of the war, local administrations existed, and two years later, elections took place.
Democracy was not an empty word, and it drew on German traditions.
Of course, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
However, there is still much to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular warrant mention.
The first is of an economic nature, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
Democracy takes root more certainly in a context of economic revival.
One must first have initiative, from individuals eager to bring an end to a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with a head start.
Wherefore the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
In a similar way, the European Union has assisted former communist countries and continues to support them in their endeavors.
The other lesson, of a moral order, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials rendered the guilt of Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany has not undertaken its long journey by dwelling on the past.
In fact, many have described the years of Adenauer after 1949 as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi personalities had remained in their posts.
In a way, the country was ignoring its past to move forward into the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany has come to terms with its past, with considerable success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other ravaged countries are therefore misleading.
Despite this, Poland followed a similar path after 1989 in its own way: first the novelty, then an attempt to come to terms with the past.
In the end, that's a better approach.
In Europe, May 8, 2005, is an opportunity to look back on the past with sadness and anger, but also to look towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and thus filled with hope.
